TY  - JOUR
T1  - Management Information Systems: Appreciation and Involvement
AU  - Swanson, E. Burton
Y1  - 1974/10/01
PY  - 1974
DA  - 1974/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.21.2.178
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.21.2.178
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 178
EP  - 188
VL  - 21
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Failures in the implementation of management information systems (?MIS's?) can be attributed in part to a lack of managerial ?involvement? and ?appreciation.? The concepts of involvement and appreciation are defined, and their measurement in a real-world research setting is presented. The testing of several hypotheses in this setting indicates that managers who involve themselves with the MIS will appreciate the system, and that managers who are uninvolved will be unappreciative.
AB  - Failures in the implementation of management information systems (?MIS's?) can be attributed in part to a lack of managerial ?involvement? and ?appreciation.? The concepts of involvement and appreciation are defined, and their measurement in a real-world research setting is presented. The testing of several hypotheses in this setting indicates that managers who involve themselves with the MIS will appreciate the system, and that managers who are uninvolved will be unappreciative.
